In [7]:
#function to stats
def image_stats(directory):
    widths = []
    heights = []
    file_sizes = []
    for filename in os.listdir(directory):
        file_path = os.path.join(directory, filename)
        with Image.open(file_path) as img:
            widths.append(img.width)
            heights.append(img.height)
            file_sizes.append(os.path.getsize(file_path) / 1024)  # KB
    
    stats_df = pd.DataFrame({
        'Width': widths,
        'Height': heights,
        'File Size (KB)': file_sizes
    })
    
    return stats_df.describe()

In [10]:
#function for image distribution
def plot_image_distributions(stats_df, title):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))
    
    sns.histplot(stats_df['Width'], bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[0], color='skyblue')
    axes[0].set_title('Width Distribution')
    
    sns.histplot(stats_df['Height'], bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[1], color='lightgreen')
    axes[1].set_title('Height Distribution')
    
    sns.histplot(stats_df['File Size (KB)'], bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[2], color='salmon')
    axes[2].set_title('File Size Distribution')
    
    fig.suptitle(title)
    plt.show()

  • File Size Distribution: The file size histogram for dog images indicates that the majority are smaller than 2000 KB, with some exceptions.

Cat Image Distributions:

  • Height Distribution: The height of cat images also generally falls below 2000 pixels, with a few taller ones.

  • File Size Distribution: Like dog images, most cat images have a file size under 2000 KB, with a few larger files.

In [12]:
#function for random images
def display_sample_images(directory, title, num_samples=5):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
    for i, filename in enumerate(random.sample(os.listdir(directory), num_samples)):
        img_path = os.path.join(directory, filename)
        img = Image.open(img_path)
        plt.subplot(1, num_samples, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(img)
        plt.title(filename.split('.')[0])
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.suptitle(title)
    plt.show()

In [15]:
# Function to split data
def split_data(source_dir, train_dir, validation_dir, test_dir, split_train=0.7, split_val=0.15):
    files = os.listdir(source_dir)
    train_files, test_files = train_test_split(files, test_size=1-split_train, random_state=42)
    val_files, test_files = train_test_split(test_files, test_size=split_val/(1-split_train), random_state=42)
    
    for file in train_files:
        shutil.move(os.path.join(source_dir, file), train_dir)
    for file in val_files:
        shutil.move(os.path.join(source_dir, file), validation_dir)
    for file in test_files:
        shutil.move(os.path.join(source_dir, file), test_dir)

base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(150, 150, 3))
In [28]:
# Freeze the layers of the base model
for layer in base_model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False
In [29]:
# Add new layers for our binary classification task
x = Flatten()(base_model.output)
x = Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x) 
predictions = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

Model Loss Graph:

  • The blue line (Train) shows the model's training loss, which decreases sharply at the beginning and then continues to decline more gradually. Lower loss values indicate better model performance on the training set.

  • The orange line (Validation) shows the loss on the validation set. It has some fluctuations but generally stays below the training loss or close to it, suggesting that the model is not overfitting significantly to the training data.

In [38]:
from sklearn.metrics import PrecisionRecallDisplay
#extract the labels from test generator
y_true = test_generator.classes

predictions = model.predict(test_generator)

# Assuming binary classification 
y_score = predictions.flatten()
display = PrecisionRecallDisplay.from_predictions(y_true, y_score)
display.ax_.set_title("Precision-Recall curve")
plt.show()

188/188  105s 555ms/step

  • Precision (y-axis) represents the ratio of true positive predictions to the total number of positive predictions (true positives + false positives).

  • Recall (x-axis), also known as sensitivity or true positive rate, is the ratio of true positives to the actual number of positives (true positives + false negatives).

  • The Area Under the Curve (AP) for this classifier is 0.96, which is very high. An AP of 1 would mean a perfect model; thus, a score of 0.96 suggests the model has a high precision across all levels of recall, which means it labels positive instances very accurately and also retrieves almost all positive instances.

# Convert probabilities to binary predictions threshold of 0.5
y_pred = (predictions.flatten() > 0.5).astype(int)

# Find misclassified examples
misclassified_idxs = np.where(y_pred != y_true)[0]

# Display some misclassified examples
sample_idxs = np.random.choice(misclassified_idxs, 5, replace=False)
for idx in sample_idxs:
    img_path = test_generator.filepaths[idx]
    img = Image.open(img_path)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.title(f"True: {y_true[idx]}, Pred: {y_pred[idx]}")
    plt.show()

Conclusions:¶

Model Training: Three models were trained:

  • A basic CNN (Model 1) showed moderate performance improvement during training, with a final accuracy of around 67% on the test set.
  • A slightly more complex CNN (Model 2) had slight highperformance, with a test accuracy of approximately 70%.
  • A VGG16-based model, likely fine-tuned on the dataset, showed superior performance with an accuracy of almost 89% on the test set.

  • Model Evaluation: The models' performance was evaluated using accuracy and loss metrics. The VGG16-based model was the best performer among the three, indicating that pre-trained models can be highly effective when fine-tuned for specific tasks.

  • Precision-Recall Curve: A precision-recall curve with an area under the curve (AP) of 0.96 was generated for one of the models, demonstrating high precision and recall levelsindicating excellent model performance for the positive class.

  • Error Analysis: Misclassified examples were identified to visually inspect the model's errors, which is a common practice to understand and improve model performance.
